 Scars have scars. In many cases, they fade, but most cases they help us to recognize our history and the things we have gone through, and some may bring us to bitter regret. Our wounds spill deep into history and have long lasting effects. Some scratches and frights may be caused by war and death, but there is always the permanent scar left from the disease and suffering forced into our land. San Antonio, in southwestern Texas, was originally located on the north

San Antonio, in southwestern Texas, was originally located on the north bank of the San Antonio River. After the Mexican War of Independence in 1822, General Antonio Lopez de Santa Anna allowed an American craftsmen, John Aguillier, and his partner to construct a bridge across the river. They laid fresh soil to the north side of the river, thus increasing land. Men of San Antonio picked the north bank as their permanent location.
